<p>If you want to use another one, just replace <code>polkit-gnome</code> with the other package name.</p>
<p>But installing it isn&rsquo;t enough — you also need to set it to start automatically. Why? Here&rsquo;s the reason:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>If you are using a graphical environment, make sure that a graphical authentication agent is installed and <a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Autostarting" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">autostarted</a> on login.</p>
<p>— <a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Polkit#Authentication_agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Arch Wiki</a></p>

</blockquote><p>In short, if you want to use it, you need to keep this program running&hellip;</p>
<p>That&rsquo;s about it. If you want the full meaning, go ask Google Translate.</p>
<p>Next, I need to figure out how to start it&hellip;</p>
<p>Actually, you can just run the path listed on the wiki directly in the terminal:</p>
